ok, here's a bunch of links that should get you started, but I couldn't find one that did exactly what you wanted.  I'm pretty sure I've seen one before, but I can't find it.  Maybe I'll look some more.  I think the basic procedure is to use a layer mask and a gradient with two layers.<br>
<br>
Part of the reason people aren't very helpful is that you're asking sort of an advanced question.  If you have no familiarity with ps, then it would be sort of hard to explain every step here.<br>
<br>
Also try these sites for some more general tutorials.<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.designsbymark.com/">www.designsbymark.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.thinkdan.com/">www.thinkdan.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.planetphotoshop.com/">www.planetphotoshop.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.phong.com/">www.phong.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
[edit]<br>
<br>
Ok, I decided to play around and I'm going to give you a basic idea what to do, but you may need to read the ps help to understand what I'm saying for some of it since I'm going to give the tool names.<br>
<br>
1) open up both images you want to use<br>
2) go to one of them.  go to Edit in Quick Mask Mode (press Q)<br>
3) now use a Gradient to select some of the picture<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp a) use a linear gradient that goes from black to white<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp b) starting from the left, pull the gradient so that it only goes<br>
           about 75% of the way across the image<br>
4) go back to normal mode by pressing Q<br>
5) press ctrl-c to copy the selection you've just made<br>
6) Now, go to the other image<br>
7) create a new layer on top of the image and paste the selection you made onto it.  It should now look like it's blending.<br>
<br>
You'll need to play with the gradient a bit to get it the way you want it to look.  That was the hardest part for me. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udynamiteneon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DynamiteNeon</A> at: 1/1/02 10:54:19 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufutura2001.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Futura2001</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(1/2/02 3:04:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2651.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.att.net/~polysin/Futura_Copy.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmm...</span><hr size=1> There is a much easier way to get a blend, well maybe not as easy as merely changing the transparency, but you actually get a blend...<br>
Okay, go to your gradient, choose a color, now go to options and edit, now go to the gradient that says &quot;Foreground to Transparent&quot; use that on a new layer.  Now, get your two images up in the same file, everything should be the same size.  Now, go hide everything except the gradient layer, select color range, now set your fuzziness pretty high, like 90-130 depending on what you need, don't worry if the selection looks sudden, when you clear away the junk, it will not be to sudden.  Hide the Gradient layer while keeping the selection, go to the layer that you want on top and click the delete button, you should now have a perfect blend between to pics.  You can now delete the gradient layer and flatten the image.<br>
